    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1969-03-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1969-03-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="12"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d12">
                <head>12. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from">Kissinger</persName>) to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRM1" type="to">Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d12fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 595, Country Files, Middle East,
                        India, Vol. I, Jan 69–Sept 69. Confidential. Sent for action. No drafting
                        information appears on the memorandum. <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> initialed his approval of the recommendation.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d12fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> approved a recommendation from
                        Kissinger involving the subsidized sale of food to India.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1969-03-20"
                        >March 20, 1969</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT:</head>
                    <item>Economic Policy Toward India</item>
                </list>
                <p>In line with our planned new procedure to give you a chance to review our
                    economic aid policy in major aid-receiving countries once a year, we have set in
                    motion papers on aid to India to come to you in April. This will be shortly
                    after the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> discussion of general aid
                    policy.</p>
                <p>However, a food aid program for India is in the works that should go ahead before
                    that date. It involves sale of $30 million worth of rice and vegetable oil and
                    $25 million worth of sorghum. The reasons for letting these move ahead at their
                    normal pace are: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>The Department of Agriculture wants to move rice as quickly as
                            possible. The <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss> heavily overproduced
                            last year to meet Vietnam requirements which did not turn out to be
                            nearly so high as expected. Agriculture wants to avoid the cost of
                            buying and storing the surplus.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>The Indians are anxious to get the sorghum. While the issue is not
                            starvation this year, this low-price grain sold through their fair price
                            shops helps keep urban food prices down.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Both these programs are follow-ons to an ongoing <gloss target="#t_FY1"
                        >FY</gloss> 1969 food aid program ($170 million). The programs you will
                    review next month will include a $150 million new wheat and cotton program, the
                    entire development lending program for <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1970
                    and a few cleanup loans for <gloss target="#t_FY1">FY</gloss> 1969.</p>
                <p>I would be inclined to stand aside and let Agriculture and <gloss
                        target="#t_AID1">AID</gloss> go ahead with these programs in their normal
                    way. However, I do not want to tell them they are free to do so if you would
                    prefer to review them in detail.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="underline">Recommendation</hi>: That you approve the scenario outlined
                    above-wallowing the on-going sales to proceed and planning an over-all review of
                    the next year’s Indian aid program in April.</p>
                <p>Approve<lb/>I’d like to see them<lb/>Other</p>
            </div>
